# Approach 2: Dutch National Flag Algorithm (Optimal)

## Idea

Use three pointers:

```java
low  -> boundary of 0s
mid  -> current element being processed
high -> boundary of 2s
```

Maintain the following regions:

```text
0 to low-1      -> all 0s
low to mid-1    -> all 1s
mid to high     -> unsorted region
high+1 to n-1   -> all 2s
```

Initially:

```text
[ Unsorted Array ]
 low
 mid
                high
```

---

## Algorithm

### Case 1: nums[mid] == 0

This element belongs to the left section.

* Swap `nums[low]` and `nums[mid]`
* Increment both `low` and `mid`

```java
swap(low, mid);
low++;
mid++;
```

---

### Case 2: nums[mid] == 1

This element is already in its correct middle section.

```java
mid++;
```

---

### Case 3: nums[mid] == 2

This element belongs to the right section.

* Swap `nums[mid]` and `nums[high]`
* Decrement `high`

```java
swap(mid, high);
high--;
```

⚠️ Do **not** increment `mid` here because the element swapped from the right side has not been processed yet.

---

## Code

```java
class Solution {
    public void sortColors(int[] nums) {

        int low = 0;
        int mid = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while (mid <= high) {

            if (nums[mid] == 0) {

                int temp = nums[low];
                nums[low] = nums[mid];
                nums[mid] = temp;

                low++;
                mid++;
            }

            else if (nums[mid] == 1) {
                mid++;
            }

            else {

                int temp = nums[mid];
                nums[mid] = nums[high];
                nums[high] = temp;

                high--;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

---

# Why Don't We Increment `mid` When We Find a `2`?

Example:

```java
[1, 2, 0]
```

Current:

```text
low = 0
mid = 1
high = 2
```

Swap `nums[mid]` and `nums[high]`:

```java
[1, 0, 2]
```

Now the new element at `mid` is `0`.

It has not been processed yet.

Therefore:

```java
high--;
```

but

```java
mid stays the same
```

so that the new element can be examined.

